{"cursor":"16366","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"A 'mental model' is an explanation of someone's thought process about how\nsomething works in the real world. It is a representation of the surrounding\nworld, the relationships between its various parts and a person's intuitive\nperception about his or her own acts and their consequences. Mental models can\nhelp shape behaviour and set an approach to solving problems (akin to a personal\nalgorithm) and doing tasks.\n","linknr":249,"url":"Mental_model","recorded":1362374859,"links":30,"instances":["psychology","abstract"],"pdf":["http://proverbs.cz/media/art/SM_ST.pdf","http://proverbs.cz/media/art/SM_ST.pdf","http://web.mit.edu/jsterman/www/ford_sterman_elicit_1.pdf","http://web.mit.edu/jsterman/www/ford_sterman_elicit_1.pdf","http://mentalmodels.princeton.edu/papers/2005HistoryMentalModels.pdf","http://cogsci.bme.hu/~babarczy/Orak/BMEpostgrad/semantics/2005spring/Johnson-Lairdmental_models.pdf","http://www.roblesdelatorre.com/gabriel/GR-RS-Estimating-Internal-Models.pdf"],"categories":["Scientific modeling","Cognitive psychology","Information","Information science","Cognitive science","Thought","Conceptual models","Cognitive modeling"],"headings":["Overview","History","Mental models and reasoning","Mental models in system dynamics","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Smycka1eng.png/230px-Smycka1eng.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Smycka2eng.png/180px-Smycka2eng.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Smycka3eng.png/180px-Smycka3eng.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/imag